    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Comparative Terms</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Distinguishing 'Texican' from 'Texan' and 'Texasian'</h2><ul><li>'Texan' broadly refers to any Texas resident</li><li>'Texasian' is a less common, inclusive term</li><li>'Texican' specifically denotes Mexican heritage in Texas</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">While 'Texan' and 'Texasian' are general terms for Texas residents, 'Texican' uniquely identifies those with Mexican cultural roots, reflecting historical and ethnic distinctions important in Texas history. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A person of Anglo-American descent living in Texas would be called a Texan, whereas a Mexican-descended settler might identify as a Texican.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare and contrast the implications of these three terms in historical and cultural contexts.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Treating these terms as interchangeable without recognizing ethnic and historical nuances.</p></div></div>",
