    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Geography</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Geographic Regions of Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Texicans primarily settled in fertile river valleys and coastal plains</li><li>Major settlement areas included the Brazos, Colorado, and Guadalupe river basins</li><li>Proximity to water sources influenced agriculture and trade</li><li>Settlements often clustered near natural resources and transportation routes</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlements were strategically located in regions offering fertile land and access to waterways, which supported farming, ranching, and trade. These geographic choices shaped their lifestyle and economic activities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The Brazos River valley provided rich soil for crops and a transportation route for goods, making it a hub for Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a map of early Texas and identify why Texicans might have chosen specific river valleys for settlement.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans settled randomly without regard to natural resources or geography.</p></div></div>",
