    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Rural and Urban Settlement Patterns of the Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texicans lived mostly in rural settlements with small villages and ranches</li><li>Few large towns existed; settlements were dispersed but connected by trails</li><li>Community centers often included a church, market, and meeting place</li><li>Settlement patterns reflected a blend of Spanish colonial and frontier influences</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican communities were typically small and spread out, reflecting a rural lifestyle centered on agriculture and ranching. Their settlement layout combined traditional Spanish colonial elements with frontier adaptations. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A typical Texican village might have a central plaza with a church and market, surrounded by ranches and farms connected by dirt trails.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how rural settlement patterns might affect social life and community cooperation among Texicans.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Confusing Texican settlements with large, densely populated urban centers common in other regions.</p></div></div>",
