      "secnum": "Deep Dive 25",
      "h": "Spanish Colonial Foundations of Texican Identity",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The Texicans inherited many cultural elements from Spanish colonial governance, including language, religion, and legal traditions. These influences persisted even as political control shifted.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Spanish colonial rule shaped early Texican social structures and traditions</li><li>Language, religion (Catholicism), and legal systems reflected Spanish origins</li><li>Land grant policies influenced settlement and land use patterns</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Many Texican families practiced Catholicism and celebrated Spanish religious festivals, maintaining cultural continuity despite political changes.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify specific Spanish cultural elements that might still be visible in Texican communities today.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican culture was purely Anglo-American without recognizing deep Spanish roots.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
