      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> After Mexico gained independence, Texicans navigated a new political landscape that blended Spanish colonial legacies with Mexican national identity, while also facing increasing Anglo-American influence.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexican independence introduced new political and cultural dynamics</li><li>Texicans adapted Spanish traditions under Mexican law and governance</li><li>Mexican policies encouraged Anglo-American immigration, complicating identity</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texicans participated in Mexican political institutions but also welcomed Anglo settlers, leading to cultural hybridity and tensions.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how Mexican governance might have altered Texican cultural practices or loyalties.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing Mexican rule as a simple continuation of Spanish control without recognizing its distinct impact.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
