    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">27</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Anglo-American Immigrants and Texican Society</h2><ul><li>Anglo settlers brought English language and Protestant beliefs</li><li>Cultural differences created social and political tensions</li><li>Texicans often acted as cultural intermediaries between Anglo and Mexican worlds</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The influx of Anglo-American immigrants introduced new cultural elements that contrasted with Texican Spanish-Mexican traditions, leading to both conflict and cultural exchange. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans sometimes served as translators or negotiators between Anglo settlers and Mexican authorities, reflecting their bicultural competence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how Anglo immigration influenced Texican cultural practices and social roles.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans rejected Anglo culture entirely rather than adapting selectively.</p></div></div>",
