      "secnum": "Deep Dive 37",
      "h": "Diverse Political Loyalties Among Texicans",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans were politically active during the Texas Revolution, with loyalties divided between Mexican rule and the push for Texan independence. Their involvement in local governance reflected these tensions and shaped revolutionary politics.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans held diverse political views during the Texas Revolution</li><li>Some supported Mexican governance, others favored independence</li><li>Texicans participated in local councils and provisional governments</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican leaders like José Antonio Navarro advocated for Texan rights within Mexico before supporting independence.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how Texican political participation influenced the direction of the Texas Revolution.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported independence without recognizing internal divisions.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
