    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources Introduction",
    "num": "49",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">49</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources Introduction</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Why Primary Sources Matter for Texican History</h2><ul><li>Primary sources offer direct evidence from the Texican era</li><li>They reveal personal perspectives, legal contexts, and social conditions</li><li>Interpreting these sources requires understanding historical context and bias</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources such as letters, legal documents, and newspapers provide authentic insights into the lives and identities of the Texicans. However, these documents must be carefully analyzed to account for the context in which they were created and the perspectives they represent. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican settler may show personal views on Mexican governance, illustrating divided loyalties during the Texas Revolution.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a primary source excerpt and identify what it reveals about Texican identity or political stance.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming primary sources are unbiased or fully representative of all Texicans without considering context or author perspective.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 49",
      "h": "Understanding the Nature of Primary Sources",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Primary sources such as letters, legal documents, and newspapers provide authentic insights into the lives and identities of the Texicans. However, these documents must be carefully analyzed to account for the context in which they were created and the perspectives they represent.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Primary sources offer direct evidence from the Texican era</li><li>They reveal personal perspectives, legal contexts, and social conditions</li><li>Interpreting these sources requires understanding historical context and bias</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A letter from a Texican settler may show personal views on Mexican governance, illustrating divided loyalties during the Texas Revolution.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine a primary source excerpt and identify what it reveals about Texican identity or political stance.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming primary sources are unbiased or fully representative of all Texicans without considering context or author perspective.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
    }
