    "id": "slide50",
    "eyebrow": "Primary Source Types",
    "num": "50",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">50</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Types</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Primary Source Types on Texicans</h2><ul><li>Personal letters and diaries reveal individual experiences</li><li>Legal documents show governance, land claims, and disputes</li><li>Newspapers provide public discourse and political opinions</li><li>Official records document military and administrative actions</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Different types of primary sources offer varied insights into Texican life. Personal letters can show daily life and loyalties, legal records reveal the framework of authority and property, newspapers capture public debates, and official records document formal events and decisions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A land grant document illustrates how Texicans acquired and defended property under Mexican law.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify which type of primary source would best help understand Texican political views and why.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Treating all primary sources as equally informative without considering their purpose or audience.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 50",
      "h": "Analyzing Different Primary Source Types",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Different types of primary sources offer varied insights into Texican life. Personal letters can show daily life and loyalties, legal records reveal the framework of authority and property, newspapers capture public debates, and official records document formal events and decisions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Personal letters and diaries reveal individual experiences</li><li>Legal documents show governance, land claims, and disputes</li><li>Newspapers provide public discourse and political opinions</li><li>Official records document military and administrative actions</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A land grant document illustrates how Texicans acquired and defended property under Mexican law.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify which type of primary source would best help understand Texican political views and why.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Treating all primary sources as equally informative without considering their purpose or audience.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
    }
