      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Newspapers from the Texican era provide a window into public discourse and political tensions. Analyzing articles and editorials reveals how Texicans expressed identity and responded to events.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from guides.library.yale.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Newspapers capture debates, announcements, and political views</li><li>They reflect the diversity of opinions among Texicans</li><li>Editorial bias and censorship must be considered</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>An editorial supporting Texas independence shows one faction’s perspective during the revolution.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze a newspaper excerpt to identify the author’s stance and intended audience.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming newspapers represent unanimous public opinion without recognizing editorial slant.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> guides.library.yale.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p>"
