    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">60</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Section Summary</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Mastering Primary Source Analysis for Texican History</h2><ul><li>Primary sources provide authentic but complex insights into Texican life</li><li>Critical interpretation requires attention to context, bias, and source type</li><li>Synthesizing multiple sources reveals the diversity of Texican identities and experiences</li><li>These skills are essential for understanding early Texas history</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">This section has equipped learners with tools to analyze and interpret primary sources, fostering a deeper and more nuanced understanding of the Texicans and their historical context. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Reviewing a letter, legal record, and newspaper together to form a balanced view of Texican political loyalties.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Reflect on how primary source analysis changes your perception of Texican history.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Neglecting to question sources or integrate multiple perspectives.</p></div></div>",
